article.description: Chris Webber scored 20 points of his 28 points in the second half and the streaking Sacramento Kings held the reeling Cleveland Cavaliers to one basket in the fourth quarter en route to an 91-85 victory.
article.headline: Wagner's 17-point debut can't halt Cavs' skid

images.name: Wagner_Dajuan 021126 inline
images.caption: Dajuan Wagner debuted with 17 points for the Cavaliers.

article.linkText: Wagner's 17-point NBA debut can't halt Cavs' skid
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Once the shots started dropping for Chris Webber, they hardly stopped. Webber scored 28 points -- 20 in the second half -- Tuesday night as the Sacramento Kings won their sixth straight, 91-85 over the tumbling Cleveland Cavaliers, who have dropped 11 in a row. After missing six of his first seven shots, Webber made 10 of 12 as the Kings beat the Cavs for the second time this season. "In the first half, I had open shots and they just didn't go down,'' said Webber, who wears a protective wrap on his right hand to protect a cracked knuckle. "In the second half, I tried to mix it up, sort of catch and shoot, take my time. I'm glad I put them down.'' Bobby Jackson added 19 points and Gerald Wallace 15 for Sacramento, which held the Cavs to one field goal -- a 3-pointer by Bimbo Coles -- in the fourth quarter. The Cavs missed their first 10 shots and went 1-of-14 in the final period while remaining winless since beating the Los Angeles Lakers on Nov. 5. Cleveland scored 16 points in the fourth quarter, 13 on free throws. But it wasn't all bad for Cleveland. The Cavs finally got to use rookie guard Dajuan Wagner, who finished with 17 points before fouling out of his NBA debut. Wagner had been sidelined since training camp, and was hospitalized last month with a bladder infection before undergoing surgery to have a blood clot removed. "He played very, very well,'' Cavs coach John Lucas said of the first-round draft pick. "There were a whole lot of positives.'' The 6-foot-2 shooting guard showed why the Cavs selected him with the No. 6 overall pick, featuring an assortment of strong moves to the basket and a nice outside touch. Wagner, whose father, Milt, played in the NBA, said he wasn't nervous on his opening night. "I thought I could have done better, but I did all right,'' the 19-year-old said. "It was comfortable. I wasn't nervous. Growing up in Camden (N.J.), you don't get nervous playing basketball.'' Ricky Davis led Cleveland with 22 points and Zydrunas Ilgauskas had 16. Despite their atrocious shooting, the Cavs were within 85-83 with 2:19 remaining. However, Webber hit a jump hook in the lane, and with the Kings up by three, Wallace wrestled the ball away underneath and hit a putback while falling down to make it 89-84 with 37 seconds left. Webber, who went just 2-for-9 from the floor in the first half, scored eight points as the Kings opened the third quarter with a 10-2 run to take a 54-52 lead. After he dunked to end the spurt, Webber hung on the rim and glared at Cavs coach John Lucas, who had tried to strike up a conversation with the Kings forward at halftime. Webber had good reason to ignore Lucas. "I like coach Lucas a lot, but he has gotten me out of my game a lot of times,'' Webber said. "I'm sure glad I didn't hear him. But that look wasn't for him. It was sort of, OK, now we mean business.'' Webber scored 12 points in the quarter on 6-of-7 shooting and added three assists, including one on a gorgeous behind-the-back bounce pass to a cutting Doug Christie. "I love making a play like that as much, maybe more, than a dunk,'' Webber said. "We practice that very play.'' Wagner, who once scored 100 points in a high school game, didn't take long to attempt his first shot as a pro, misfiring on a 15-foot jumper just 26 seconds into the first. He got his first basket on a 7-footer with 8:44 remaining in the half, and 18 seconds later, dunked an alley-oop pass from Jumaine Jones that brought the Gund Arena crowd to its feet. "That's what I like,'' the quiet Wagner said. "That's only going to get me to play harder.'' Wagner drained a pair of 3-pointers in the final 1:51 of the half and fed Davis for a layup at the buzzer to put Cleveland ahead 50-44 at halftime.

Game notes
Long-time broadcaster Joe Tait called his 2,500th game with the Cavaliers. The club celebrated the occasion by giving away 5,000 "Joe Tait Bobble-belly Dolls'' as a tribute to the rotund Tait. ... Kings F Peja Stojakovic missed his second straight game with plantar fasciitis in his right foot, His status is day-to-day. Hedo Turkoglu started in his place and shot 1-for-5 in 24 minutes. ... Lucas said C Chris Mihm (strained left hamstring) and F Darius Miles (left knee tendinitis) are "a ways away'' from being activated. ... Jackson is the only Kings player to start all 16 games this season. ... The Kings are 10-0 when outshooting an opponent from the field. ... Coles must feel old. He was a rookie teammate of Milt Wagner 11 years ago in Miami. Dajuan was seven then.
